    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-07-09T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-07-09T17:00:00-05:00" n="806"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d806">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.796/207a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Second Secretary of Legation in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">at Nanking</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-07-09T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 9, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>58. Your 85, April 29, 10 a.m. Press item under Shanghai date line of July 2
                    reports Military Attaché of Japanese Embassy in China as stating that one of the
                    secret clauses of the Tangku truce<note n="21" xml:id="d806fn21">For the Tangku
                        Truce Agreement between the Chinese and Japanese military authorities,
                        signed at Tangku May 31, 1933, see <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_120">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931– 1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 120</ref>.</note> granted to Japan the
                    right to “establish civil aviation in China.”</p>
                <p>Press item of July 6 reports Chinese Consulate General at New York as stating,
                    with reference to above report, “Concerning this report, this Consulate General
                    has received government instructions to declare that there is no secret
                    provision or clause whatsoever in the Tangku Truce Agreement. Nor is it a fact
                    that the Chinese Government has ever granted to Japan the permission to
                    establish civil aviation in China.”</p>
                <p>Department desires that Legation continue to follow closely and to report
                    promptly aviation developments in China with particular reference to possible
                    effects on American interests.</p>
                <p>Inform Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
